Introduction


This practical is all about subtyping. Subtyping is a kind of inheritance where the subtype can always be used as a substitute for the supertype.

For the fundamentals, you will implement various types of pseudorandom number generators (PRNG). The various generators you will implement will be subtypes of the Prng class. The end goal of the fundamentals is to make you implement a stream cipher that was used to secure 2G communications.

Then, regarding the enhancements, you will implement something similar to the numeric type tree of Lisp. The goal is to perform some kind of arithmetic on rationals, while avoiding as possible the loss of precision caused by working with floats.

Finally, in the proficiencies, you will be implementing a small game with a top down view, but using special types that will allow us to perform bulk actions more easily. The goal is to understand how modern engines, such as Godot or Unity, manage types altogether, without arrays and with infinite position precision.

Warning(s)
  • Anytime the keyword MUST is used, the definition is an absolute requirement, and will be tested. Not complying with the specification will lead to a malus.
  • Anytime the keyword SHOULD is used, it is not a requirement, however, complying with the specification will probably be beneficial for you. For instance, the definition may include tips for a cleaner of simpler implementation. These specifications are advice for you, and will not be tested if it is not specified otherwise. You can choose to ignore them at your own risk, you will not be penalized.
  • On the other hand, anytime the keyword MAY is used, the specification is truly optional. You may or not follow the specification, without worrying about any consequences.

A pseudorandom number generator, denoted as PRNG during this practical, is an algorithm which aims to generate a sequence of numbers that appears random.

You will implement various kind of pseudorandom number generators (PRNG), which will take the form of subtypes of an abstract class Prng, meaning that whenever someone needs a pseudorandom number generator, we can provide him whatever subtype we choose, and it should still fit his needs.

In this practical, an instance of a Prng will always possess a State, a 64-bit integer that represent its current state. The output of a generator will always be determined fully by its state, which means, if we assign the same state to two generators of the same nature, they will produce the exact same sequence.

All instances of Prng will implement a method Next, that returns a randomly generated byte.

During this part, you will need to work directly on the binary representation of some integers. However, the usage of bitwise operators is never mandatory.


Fundamentals/Warmup.cs


This section will serve as a warm-up. You will implement some methods manipulating the binary representation of integers, such as converting an integer to a bit array, or counting the number of 1s in the binary representation of an integer.

You SHOULD use bitwise operators for an efficient implementation of these methods when you can, although it is not mandatory. These operators allows you to directly work on the binary representation of integers, without having to iterate through them everytime.

You can check the MSDN documentation for bitwise operators here.

All of these methods may be helpful later on during this practical. You MAY call them in the following sections.

A bit array is an integer structure which is not limited in size. This is very useful when we want to work with very big integers that may exceed 64 bits, and therefore may overflow if we would treat them with a fixed-size integer type.

In this exercise, we will represent a bit array as a List<bool>. The bool type is used to represent a bit. The value true represent a 1, and false represent a 0.

In our implementation, the bit at index iii always have a weight of 2i2^i2i, which means, the least significant bit is located at index 0, and the most significant bit is located at the end of the list.

Warning(s)
In the standard binary representation of an integer, the least significant bit is the rightmost one. However, in a bitarray, we prefer writing the element at index 0 first, which is the least significant bit.

Because of this, when you display any number in its binary representation and its bitarray representation, you should notice that the bits are "flipped".

Information
For instance, RSA encryption works nowadays with keys that are integers more than 1000-bit long!



Warning(s)
In our implementation, the value 0 is represented with a list containing a single false element.

Except for this value, no leading zeroes should ever be present, which means, a valid bit array must always end with true.

Any bit array that does not represent 0 and ends with false is denoted as invalid.

Your functions MAY NOT check the validity of the bit arrays given as input, as we will always provide them with valid bit arrays. However, your functions MUST NOT return an invalid bit array.

Hint(s)
You can convert a number in binary by repeatedly dividing it by two. When a number is even, its last bit is be 0, otherwise its last bit is 1. When you divide a number by two, you discard its last bit, and you may now process the following bits.

The following image shows how to get the binary representation of 42 by repeatedly dividing it by two. The number in red is the remainder modulo 2. It is zero when the number is even, and one when the number is odd.



Prototype(s)
public static List<bool> LongToBitArray(ulong value) { }

Code example(s)
List<bool> bitarray42 = Warmup.LongToBitArray(42);
// bitarray42 == { false, true, false, true, false, true }

List<bool> bitarray0 = Warmup.LongToBitArray(0);
// bitarray0 == { false }

List<bool> bitarray255 = Warmup.LongToBitArray(255);
// bitarray255 == { true, true, true, true, true, true, true, true }

The following method will perform the reverse operation, that is, retrieving the integer value from a bit array.
As we are using the type ulong, which is an unsigned 64-bit integer type, your code MUST throw an OverflowException if the provided bit array contains more than 64 elements.

Hint(s)
There exist mainly two ways to read an integer from its binary form:
  • If you read the integer from the most significant bit to the least, you can perform the opposite of the conversion from decimal to binary: successive multiplications by two.
  • Otherwise, you can simply iterate in the order you prefer,
    and for each bit set to one, you add 2i2^i2i, where iii is
    the position of the bit.
You can easily get power of twos using bit-shifting: 1UL << i returns 2i2^i2i as a ulong.

Warning(s)
Note that the following code will not work as intended: ulong i = 1 << 42. Even though an ulong is large enough to store the value of 2422^{42}242, the literal value 1 is an int, and the conversion to ulong is done after the shift.

Therefore, to perform this operation, we use the literal 1UL, which is an unsigned long (64-bits) storing the value 1.

Prototype(s)
public static ulong BitArrayToLong(List<bool> bitArray) { }

Code example(s)
ulong value42 = Warmup.BitArrayToLong(bitarray42);
// value42 == 42

ulong value0 = Warmup.BitArrayToLong(bitarray0);
// value0 == 0

ulong value255 = Warmup.BitArrayToLong(bitarray255);
// value255 == 255

List<bool> bitarrayLarge = new List<bool>(new bool[65]);
ulong valueLarge = Warmup.BitArrayToLong(bitarrayLarge);
// Unhandled exception. System.OverflowException: ...

You will implement a method ExtractBit that returns the bit at a specific position of an integer.

The bit that is returned is the one at the corresponding position in the array that would be returned by LongToBitArray.

However you SHOULD get this bit directly using bitwise operators instead of calling the previous method, as instanciating and populating a List is very costly.

Hint(s)
There are mainly two ways to extract a specific bit of an integer using bitwise operators:
  • The first method is called bit-masking: n & (1UL << i) will mask all the bits of n, except the i-th bit. Therefore, the result will be 0 if the i-th bit was 0, and a different value otherwise.
  • The second method is called bit-shifting: n >> i will discard the least significant bits, up to the bit in position iii (excluded). Therefore, if this value is odd, then the i-th bit was a 1, otherwise it was a 0.

Prototype(s)
public static bool ExtractBit(ulong value, uint position) { }

Code example(s)
bool leastSignificantBit = Warmup.ExtractBit(42, 0);
// leastSignificantBit == false

bool secondBit = Warmup.ExtractBit(42, 1);
// secondBit == true

bool mostSignificantBit = Warmup.ExtractBit(42, 5);
// mostSignificantBit == true

bool leadingZero = Warmup.ExtractBit(42, 6);
// leadingZero == false

You will implement a method that, given three bits, returns the bit that is present in majority, that is, the bit that is present at least twice.

Prototype(s)
public static bool MajorityVote(bool bit1, bool bit2, bool bit3) { }

Code example(s)

// unanimousTrue == true

bool majorityTrue = Warmup.MajorityVote(true, false, true);
// majorityTrue == true

bool majorityFalse = Warmup.MajorityVote(false, false, true);
// majorityFalse == false

This method returns the number of bits set to 1 in the binary representation of an integer.

Again, you SHOULD directly get this number using bitwise operations, as instanciating a list is costlier.

Prototype(s)
public static uint PopCount(ulong value) { }

Code example(s)
uint popcount42 = Warmup.PopCount(42);   // popcount42 == 3
// 42  = 0b0010_1010
uint popcount255 = Warmup.PopCount(255); // popcount255 == 8
// 255 = 0b1111_1111
uint popcount0 = Warmup.PopCount(0);     // popcount0 == 0
// 0   = 0b0000_0000
uint popcount64 = Warmup.PopCount(64);   // popcount64 == 1
// 64  = 0b0100_0000

Information
The prefix 0b is used to indicate that the number is written in its binary representation.

Underscores _ are used as number separators, they are ignored and help making large numbers easier to read.

Finally, this method returns true if the given value is a power of two.

Hint(s)
A power of two has a single 1 in its binary representation. Therefore, when nnn is a power of two, at no position there will be a 1 in both the binary representation of nnn and the binary representation of n−1n - 1n−1.

You SHOULD use this fact to directly determine if a number is a power of two, using bitwise operators, such as the bitwise AND.

Prototype(s)

Code example(s)

// twoToTheTenth == true

// twoToTheZeroth == true

// notAPowerOfTwo == false

// edgeCase == false

This file will contain the implementation of the parent abstract class Prng. All our following implementations of random number generators will be subtype of this abstract class.



Information
You may take a look at the Wikipedia page about Pseudorandom number generators for more information.

This abstract class MUST contain:
  • A public property ulong State, with a getter and a protected setter. This 64-bit integer will be used to represent the internal state of the random number generator.
  • A protected constructor, with a ulong seed as an argument. This constructor sets the internal state of the generator to the seed given as an argument.
  • The declaration of a public abstract method named Next, that will return a byte. This method will be overriden by the actual implementations. Calling this method should return a pseudorandom byte, that is, a random-looking integer between 0 and 255.

Prototype(s)

public abstract byte Next();


Fundamentals/LCG/Lcg.cs


This file will implement a simple kind of pseudorandom number generator called Linear Congruential Generator (LCG). This kind of PRNG generates random-looking integers thanks to modular arithmetic.

This file will contain an single class, Lcg, which inherits from Prng.

Information
This kind of pseudorandom number generator is one of the first generator that ever existed.

You may take a look at the Wikipedia page about linear congruential generators for more information.

A linear congruential generator is defined by four parameters:
  • the modulus, mmm;
  • the multiplier, aaa;
  • the increment, ccc;
  • the seed, X0X_0X0​.

The constructor should create an instance of Lcg from the four parameters listed above.

You MUST make three properties to store the three new parameters, named Modulus, Multiplier and Increment.

You MUST assign a public getter (but no setter) to the three new properties.

You MUST directly store the seed in the attribute State that is provided by the parent class.

You MUST use the base keyword to set the State.

The following constraints on the parameters MUST be checked:
  • the seed, the multiplier, and the increment must be less than the modulus. This implies the modulus cannot be zero. In the opposite case, you MUST throw an ArgumentException;
  • if the modulus is greater than 2322^{32}232 and is not a power of two, you MUST throw an OverflowException.

Information
The modulus should be less than 2322^{32}232, because if it is greater than 2322^{32}232, the multiplication may result in an overflow and yield incorrect results. However, this is not an issue if the modulus is a power of two, thanks to modular arithmetic by storage-bit truncation (basically, it will overflow, but the result will be correct anyway, you don't have to worry about it).

Prototype(s)
public Lcg(ulong seed, ulong multiplier, ulong increment, ulong modulus) { }

Code example(s)
Lcg validLcg = new Lcg(0, 4, 1, 9);
// validLcg.State == 0
// validLcg.Multiplier == 4
// validLcg.Increment == 1
// validLcg.Modulus == 9

Lcg wrongLcg1 = new Lcg(3, 4, 5, 5);
// Unhandled exception. System.ArgumentException: ...

Lcg wrongLcg2 = new Lcg(3, 4, 5, 9_876_543_210);
// Unhandled exception. System.OverflowException: ...

Lcg powerOfTwoLcg = new Lcg(3, 4, 5, 4_398_046_511_104);
// No exception!

To get the next state value Xn+1X_{n+1}Xn+1​ from a linear congruential generator:
  • first, the state is multiplied by the multiplier;
  • then, the increment is added to the state;
  • finally, the state is taken modulo the modulus.

More formally, if XnX_nXn​ denotes the current state of the LCG, we can express the following state of the LCG as: Xn+1=Xn×a+cmod  mX_{n+1} = X_n \times a + c \mod mXn+1​=Xn​×a+cmodm

The method Next should first update the value of the state according to this algorithm, then return the updated value of the state, modulo 256.



Hint(s)
Thanks again to the modular arithmetic by storage-bit truncation, casting the state to a byte will implicitly perform the modulo 256.

Prototype(s)
public override byte Next() { }

Code example(s)
Lcg wikiLcg = new Lcg(0, 4, 1, 9);
Console.WriteLine(wikiLcg.Next()); // 1
Console.WriteLine(wikiLcg.Next()); // 5
Console.WriteLine(wikiLcg.Next()); // 3
Console.WriteLine(wikiLcg.Next()); // 4

Lcg truncatedLcg = new Lcg(1, 10, 0, 1042);
// truncatedLcg.State == 1
Console.WriteLine(truncatedLcg.Next()); // 10
// truncatedLcg.State == 10
Console.WriteLine(truncatedLcg.Next()); // 100
// truncatedLcg.State == 100
Console.WriteLine(truncatedLcg.Next()); // 232
// truncatedLcg.State == 1000
Console.WriteLine(truncatedLcg.Next()); // 110
// truncatedLcg.State == 622

Output
1
5
3
4
10
100
232
110

Fundamentals/IRewindable.cs


This file will contain the definition of an interface, IRewindable, that can be applied to some PRNGs.

The idea is that, knowing the state of a PRNG, we may be able to rewind the PRNG to its previous states.

The interface consists of a single method, Rewind.

PRNGs conforming to this interface must implement this method, which is supposed to set the PRNG back to its previous state.

Prototype(s)
public byte Rewind();


Fundamentals/LCG/Lcg.cs


Your objective is now to make the LCG class implement the IRewindable interface.

To do so, we can invert the LCG equation: Xn−1=(Xn−c)⋅a−1mod  m,X_{n-1} = (X_n - c) \cdot a^{-1} \mod m,Xn−1​=(Xn​−c)⋅a−1modm, where a−1a^{-1}a−1 denotes the modular inverse of aaa modulo mmm.

This modular inverse may be computed thanks to the Extended Euclidean algorithm.

You will find a very detailed pseudocode of this algorithm on its Wikipedia page:

 function modular_inverse(a, m)
    t := 0;     newt := 1
    r := m;     newr := a

    while newr ≠ 0 do
        quotient := r div newr
        (t, newt) := (newt, t − quotient × newt) 
        (r, newr) := (newr, r − quotient × newr)

    if r > 1 then
        return "a is not invertible modulo m"
    if t < 0 then
        t := t + m

    return t

If the modular inverse does not exist, then the LCG is not rewindable. In that case, calling the method Rewind MUST throw a NotSupportedException.

Hint(s)
You SHOULD compute the modular inverse of aaa only once, when instanciating the LCG, and store it in a private attribute.



Warning(s)
If you chose to skip the implementation of Rewind, you MUST still make the class implement the IRewindable interface. Simply throw a NotImplementedException or you won't be graded for the other methods of the class.

Prototype(s)
public byte Rewind() { }

Code example(s)
Lcg wikiLcg2 = new Lcg(4, 4, 1, 9);

Console.WriteLine(wikiLcg2.Rewind()); // 3
Console.WriteLine(wikiLcg2.Rewind()); // 5
Console.WriteLine(wikiLcg2.Rewind()); // 1
Console.WriteLine(wikiLcg2.Rewind()); // 0

MinStdRand minStdRand2 = new MinStdRand(69);

Console.WriteLine(minStdRand2.Next());   // 139
Console.WriteLine(minStdRand2.Next());   // 239
Console.WriteLine(minStdRand2.Next());   // 7
Console.WriteLine(minStdRand2.Rewind()); // 239
Console.WriteLine(minStdRand2.Rewind()); // 139
Console.WriteLine(minStdRand2.Next());   // 239
Console.WriteLine(minStdRand2.Next());   // 7

Lcg notRewindable = new Lcg(0, 2, 0, 4);
notRewindable.Rewind();
// Unhandled exception. System.NotSupportedException: ...

Fundamentals/Drbg.cs


This file will contain a subclass of Prng to ease the implementation of some specific kind of PRNGs. As we will see pretty soon, some PRNGs are made to output random bits instead of random numbers.

These generators are called Deterministic Random Bit Generators (DRBG).

In this file, you will create an abstract subclass of Prng called Drbg. Instead of having to provide a method Next that returns a randomly generated byte, subclasses of Drbg will have to provide two simpler methods:
  • Peek, which returns a randomly generated bit, but does not change the state;
  • Clock, which updates the state of the Drbg to its next state.

The method Next will always consist of calling Peek then Clock eight times to form a random byte, so this method will be implemented only once, in this abstract subclass.

The constructor of Drbg will exactly be the same as the one of Prng.

Therefore, you MUST use the base keyword to avoid code redundancy.

Prototype(s)
protected Drbg(ulong seed) { }

All subclasses of Drbg must implement the method Peek, which returns a random bit, but does not change the state. This abstract method must therefore be present in Drbg.

Prototype(s)
public abstract bool Peek();

All subclasses of Drbg must implement the method Clock, which sets the state of the generator to its next state, but does not return anything. This abstract method must therefore be present in Drbg as well.

Prototype(s)
public abstract void Clock();

Now, you need to override the method Next by forming a byte from eight subsequent calls to Peek and Clock.

The first call to Peek should provide the most significant bit of the byte, and the eighth call should provide the least significant bit.

Warning(s)
Unlike Peek and Clock, this is not an abstract method. You need to implement it in the class Drbg.



Prototype(s)
public override byte Next() { }

Warning(s)
Since Next heavily depends on Peek and Clock, which are abstract methods, you need a subclass of Drbg in order to test the behavior of Next.

The next section will focus on the implementation of a subtype of Drbg, some basic tests for this override will be provided there.

You may want to skip the implementation of Next and get back to it once you have implemented Peek and Clock.


Fundamentals/LFSR/Lfsr.cs


This file will contain the implementation of a more widely used random number generator, named Linear-Feedback Shift Registers (LFSR for short). These kind of generators directly works on bits, and can be fully implemented using only bitwise operators. If implemented correctly, LFSRs have one of the best throughput you can get thanks to the hardware providing fast implementation of bitwise operators.

This file will contain a single class, Lfsr, which inherits from Drbg.



Information
As usual, you may find more information about Linear-Feedback Shift Registers on the Wikipedia page.

A LFSR stores a fixed-size queue of bits, denoted as the pool. The LFSR parameters consists of:
  • the size of the pool, denoted as the length of the LFSR;
  • the initial state of the pool, denoted as the seed of the LFSR;
  • a small set of positions in the pool, denoted as the taps.



The initial state of the pool is provided to you as a ulong, using the binary representation of integers. The most significant bit of the seed corresponds to the bit of the pool which will be the first to be dequeued.

This time, except for the state, you may store the parameters however you want. The way you store your parameters will not be tested.

However, you MUST still check the validity of the parameters. Namely,
  • The length must be between 1 and 64 (included), as larger length will disallow us to store the State in a 64-bit integer. In the opposite case, throw an ArgumentException.
  • All the indices in the list of taps must be valid positions inside the pool, that is, integers ranging from 0 to length - 1. In the opposite case, throw an ArgumentException.
  • All taps should be distinct. If a tap is present at least twice, throw an ArgumentException.
  • Finally, the seed should not exceed 2l2^l2l, where lll denote the length, as it would not fit in the pool otherwise. In this case, throw an ArgumentException as well.

Warning(s)
You MUST use the keyword base to set the State.

Warning(s)
Careful! It is not easy to compare the seed with 2l2^l2l when l=64l = 64l=64, since you cannot store the value 2642^{64}264 inside a 64-bit integer! A simple way to check the validity of the seed is to divide it by 2l2^l2l using a right shift. If the quotient is nonzero, the seed is invalid.

Be also very careful when you are using bit-shifts. It is not possible to shift a `ulong` by 64 as well.

Hint(s)
You SHOULD store the taps as a bitmask in a 64-bit integer, where the bit at position iii is set to 1 if there exist a tap for the index iii, and 0 otherwise.

By doing so, all the future methods will be easier to implement using bitwise operations.

You SHOULD NOT use any other structure for storing the pool, such as a bit array or a queue. Everything can be done directly in the State. If you still chose to use an external structure, do not forget to update the State to reflect your modifications on the pool.

Prototype(s)
public Lfsr(ulong seed, uint length, List<uint> taps) { }

Code example(s)
Lfsr shortLfsr = new Lfsr(5, 4, new List<uint> { 0, 3, 2 });        // OK
// shortLfsr.State == 5
Lfsr largeLfsr = new Lfsr(42, 85, new List<uint> { 1, 5, 63, 75 }); // LFSR too large
// Unhandled exception. System.ArgumentException: ...
Lfsr multiTapLfsr = new Lfsr(5, 4, new List<uint> { 2, 1, 2 });     // Duplicated taps
// Unhandled exception. System.ArgumentException: ...
Lfsr wrongTapLfsr = new Lfsr(4, 6, new List<uint> { 0, 3, 6 });     // Out of bound tap
// Unhandled exception. System.ArgumentException: ...
Lfsr wrongTapLfsr2 = new Lfsr(42, 5, new List<uint> { 0, 3, 4 });    // Seed too large
// Unhandled exception. System.ArgumentException: ...

The output of the LFSR is the bit at the dequeuing end of the pool, that is, the most significant bit of the State.

This method must return the bit which is about to be dequeued, without actually dequeuing it.

Prototype(s)
public override bool Peek() { }

Code example(s)
Lfsr fiboLfsr = new Lfsr(21, 5, new List<uint> { 1, 2, 3, 4 });
// 21 = 0b0001_0101         // Pool: ← 10101 ←
Console.WriteLine(fiboLfsr.Peek());  // true
Console.WriteLine(fiboLfsr.Peek());  // true
Console.WriteLine(fiboLfsr.State);   // 21

Lfsr fiboLfsr2 = new Lfsr(21, 6, new List<uint> { 5, 0 });
// 21 = 0b0001_0101         // Pool: ← 010101 ←
Console.WriteLine(fiboLfsr2.Peek()); // false
Console.WriteLine(fiboLfsr2.Peek()); // false
Console.WriteLine(fiboLfsr2.State);  // 21

When a LFSR generator is clocked, it starts by generating a new bit that is enqueued to the pool. To generate this bit, we simply check the number of bits set to 1 in the pool, but only looking at the positions indicated by the taps. If this number is even, we enqueue a 0, otherwise, we enqueue a 1.

Then, the LFSR dequeues a bit from the pool.



Hint(s)
If you only use the State to represent the pool, you can shift all the bits using a bit shift, then enqueue the new bit by simply adding 1 if necessary.

What is more difficult is removing the leftmost bit if it was a 1. To do this, you may use value & ((1 << count) - 1), which clears all the bits of value, after the count least significant bits.

Taking the value modulo 2count2^{\text{count}}2count may also do the trick, but remember that you cannot store 2642^{64}264.

Warning(s)
Do not forget to update the State of your generator!

The state MUST always represent exactly the pool of the LFSR, with the most significant bit of the state representing the bit at the dequeueing end of the pool (the first to be dequeued).

Information
If there is no tap, you should enqueue a 0.

Prototype(s)
public override void Clock() { }

Code example(s)
Lfsr fiboLfsr3 = new Lfsr(21, 5, new List<uint> { 1, 2, 3, 4 });
                                      // Taps:    ⇩⇩⇩⇩
// 21 = 0b0001_0101                   // Output ← 10101 ← Count of 1
Console.WriteLine(fiboLfsr3.State);   // 0b10101 = 21   ❘ two 1s (even)
fiboLfsr3.Clock();                    //        ← 01010 ↲
Console.WriteLine(fiboLfsr3.State);   // 0b01010 = 10   ❘ two 1s (even)
fiboLfsr3.Clock();                    //        ← 10100 ↲
Console.WriteLine(fiboLfsr3.State);   // 0b10100 = 20   ❘ two 1s (even)
fiboLfsr3.Clock();                    //        ← 01000 ↲
Console.WriteLine(fiboLfsr3.State);   // 0b01000 = 8    ❘ one 1  (odd)
fiboLfsr3.Clock();                    //        ← 10001 ↲
Console.WriteLine(fiboLfsr3.State);   // 0b10001 = 17

The objective here is to apply the interface IRewindable to the class Lfsr.

A LFSR is always Rewindable when there is a tap on the last index of the pool, that is, the bit that is about to be dequeued. If no such tap exist, you MUST throw a NotSupportedException.

In order to rewind a LFSR when a tap is present on the last index of the pool, you should:
  • remove the tap on the last index of the pool;
  • move all the other taps one step to the left;
  • add a tap at index 0.

With these new taps, applying the usual rule of counting the number of 1s covered by a tap will reveal the last bit that was dequeued.



Warning(s)
This method is probably the hardest of the fundamentals, and is not a requirement for any other functions. If you have too much troubles, consider implementing the rest beforehand.

However, you MUST make the class implement the IRewindable interface even if you do not implement Rewind, as otherwise we will consider your architecture to be incorrect. If you chose to skip the implementation of Rewind, simply throw a NotImplementedException or you won't be graded for the other methods.

Hint(s)
As with Lcg, you SHOULD store the "reversed taps" in a private attribute, and compute them only once, in the constructor.

Hint(s)
To respect the expected behavior of Rewind, you should rewind the state of the LFSR by 8 bits. However, you must also return the byte that led to this state, which can only be computed by rewinding the state an additional 8 times.

Therefore, an easy way to do it is to simply rewind the LFSR by 16 bits and then call Next().

Prototype(s)
public byte Rewind() { }

Code example(s)
Lfsr rewindable = new Lfsr(42, 6, new List<uint> { 1, 4, 5 });
// rewindable.State == 42
Console.WriteLine(rewindable.Next());   // 169
// rewindable.State == 34
Console.WriteLine(rewindable.Next());   // 136
// rewindable.State == 31
Console.WriteLine(rewindable.Rewind()); // 169
// rewindable.State == 34
Console.WriteLine(rewindable.Rewind()); // 15
// rewindable.State == 42

Lfsr notRewindable = new Lfsr(42, 6, new List<uint> { 1, 4 });

// Unhandled exception. System.NotSupportedException: ...

Fundamentals/LFSR/A51.cs


This will be the last generator you will have to implement to complete the fundamentals.

You will implement one of the A5 security protocol of the GSM cellular telephone standard. More precisely, you will implement the keystream of A5/1, which was a stream cipher used to secure 2G communication in 1987.

The A5/1 keystream works by using the output of three LFSRs that clocks irregularly, following a majority rule on one of their bit.

The file should contain a single class, A51, which inherits from Drbg.

Information
You may find a lot of details about the history of this stream cipher on its Wikipedia page. Like a lot of security standards of the 80s, this stream cipher is now considered broken as the NSA is now able to decrypt A5/1 messages on the fly.

The constructor of the class A51 takes a single 64-bit integer as an argument, which corresponds to the initial state of the three LFSRs:
  • The first LFSR is a LFSR of length 19, with four taps at index 13, 16, 17, and 18. Its initial state corresponds to the 19 least significant bits of the seed provided to the constructor.
  • The second LFSR is a LFSR of length 22, with two taps at index 20, and 21. Its initial state corresponds to the 22 following bits of the seed provided to the constructor.
  • The third LFSR is a LFSR of length 23, with four taps at index 7, 20, 21, and 22. Its initial state corresponds to the 23 most significant bits of the seed provided to the constructor.
You MUST store the three LFSRs in three private attributes, named _lfsr1, _lfsr2, and _lfsr3.

The State MUST always be a 64-bit integer, with its 19 least significant bits representing the State of the first LFSR, the next 22 bits representing the State of second LFSR, and the 23 most significant bits representing the state of the third LFSR.

Warning(s)
As usual, you MUST use the keyword base to set the State of your generator.

Prototype(s)
public A51(ulong seed) { }

Code example(s)
ulong seed = 0b00111000111000111000111_1100110011001100110011_1010101010101010101;
//             |        _lfsr3       | |       _lfsr2       | |     _lfsr1      |

A51 keystream = new A51(seed);
Console.WriteLine(keystream.State); // 4,099,277,975,707,276,629

Console.WriteLine(keystream._lfsr1.State);
// 0b1010101010101010101 == 349,525

Console.WriteLine(keystream._lfsr2.State);
// 0b1100110011001100110011 == 3,355,443

Console.WriteLine(keystream._lfsr3.State);
// 0b00111000111000111000111 == 1,864,135

Output

Warning(s)
As _lfsr1, _lfsr2, and _lfsr3 are private attributes, you won't be able to test this directly in your Program.cs.

Either write this code directly inside the A51 class, check the values using the debugger, or temporarily make the attributes public.

If you change the visibility to test your code, do not forget to leave the attributes private when you submit your code!

To generate a bit, the A5/1 keystream simply peeks its three internal LFSRs (without clocking them!) If the number of LFSRs that returns 1 is even, then the keystream returns a 0, otherwise it returns a 1.

Therefore, the keystream returns 1 if and only if one or three LFSRs returns a 1.



Hint(s)
Xor-ing booleans will return true if and only if the number of boolean that were true was odd.

Prototype(s)
public override bool Peek()

Code example(s)
ulong seed2 = 0b00111000111000111000111_1100110011001100110011_1010101010101010101;
//             |        _lfsr3       | |       _lfsr2       | |     _lfsr1      |

A51 keystream2 = new A51(seed2);
Console.WriteLine(keystream2.Peek()); // false

Output
False

The A5/1 keystream use an irregular clocking rule based on a majority vote on special bits of each LFSRs.

We denote as clocking bits:
  • The bit at index 8 of the pool of the first LFSR;
  • The bit at index 10 of the pool of the second LFSR;
  • The bit at index 10 of the pool of the third LFSR.

Looking at the clocking bits of the three LFSRs, we only clock the LFSRs that agrees with the majority.

For instance, if the clocking bit of the first LFSR is set to 1 and the clocking bits of the two other LFSRs are set to 0, then the majority vote is 0, so we clock the second and the third LFSRs.



Information
By doing so, we add some irregularity which makes the keystream very hard to reverse.

Because we are clocking the LFSRs that agree with the majority, there will be always at least two of the three LFSRs that clocks.

Warning(s)
Do not forget to update the value of State!

Prototype(s)
public override void Clock();

Code example(s)
ulong seed3 = 0b00111000111000111000111_1100110011001100110011_1010101010101010101;
//             |        _lfsr3       | |       _lfsr2       | |     _lfsr1      |

A51 keystream3 = new A51(seed3);
keystream3.Clock();

Console.WriteLine(keystream3._lfsr1.State);
// 0b1010101010101010101 == 349,525, did not clock

Console.WriteLine(keystream3._lfsr2.State);
// 0b1001100110011001100110 == 2,516,582, clocked

Console.WriteLine(keystream3._lfsr3.State);
// 0b01110001110001110001110 == 3,728,270, clocked

Console.WriteLine(keystream3.State); // 8,198,553,752,390,948,181
// == 0b01110001110001110001110_1001100110011001100110_1010101010101010101

Output

2516582
3728270
8198553752390948181


In Lisp (a programming language), in order to avoid loss of precision when performing simple arithmetics over the integers, there are intermediate types between the integer type and the float type.

For instance, the division of two INTEGER will return a RATIO.

Code example(s)
* (type-of 3)
(INTEGER 0 4611686018427387903)
* (type-of (/ 4 3))
RATIO

In comparison, in other languages, when you perform the division "4 / 3", either you perform the integer division and only get the integer part of the result, or a floating division is performed, and the result loses precision, since 4/3 is not possible to represent accurately using the IEEE 754 representation.

What's more, Lisp will always try reduce the type of the results to the most precise one:

Code example(s)
* (type-of (+ (/ 4 3) (/ 2 3)))
(INTEGER 0 4611686018427387903)

As you can see, the computation of "4/3 + 2/3" returned an INTEGER instead of a RATIO. This allows more efficient computations, since arithmetic on integers is often more efficient than arithmetic on rationals.

In this section, we will try to mimic the behavior of Lisp in C#, using subtyping and operator overloading.


Enhancements/Real.cs


This file will contain the parent abstract class for all the kind of numbers we will consider, named Real.

This class is purely abstract and will not provide any constructor.



All subclasses of Real must provide a property named Value with a public getter only. This property will return an approximated version of the current value of the number as a double.

Therefore, this class must indicate an abstract public getter named Value.


Enhancements/Float.cs


This file will contain the simplest kind of Real, which does not provide any kind of optimisation. The reason is, we will never be able to upgrade a Float to a smaller type accurately, since floats does not represent accurate values, but a very small range of values. For instance, the float 1.0f can represent the value 1, but it may also represent the value 1.000…001.

This file must contain a single class named Float which inherits from Real.

Start by overriding the abstract property Value with a simple public getter.

This class will provide a simple constructor which will set the value of the property.

The special values +Infinity, -Infinity, and NaN will not be tested.

Enhancements/Rational.cs


This file will contain an abstract class for all the rationals subtypes. This class must be named Rational, and must inherit from Real.

The contract that all subtypes of Rational must satisfy is that they should be able to be written in the form pq\dfrac pqqp​, where ppp and qqq are two integers.

To ensure this fact, you must create two abstract properties inside of Rational:
  • The abstract property Numerator, which will return a long, with a public getter;
  • The abstract property Denominator, which will return a ulong, with a public getter.

If a subtype successfully provides these two properties, then we may use them to automatically provide a value for the property Value. Indeed, the actual value of any rational is its numerator divided by its denominator.

Therefore, you must override the property Value with an automatic public getter, which will return the ratio between the numerator and the denominator, as a double.

Write the protected constructor of this abstract class. It will set Health to the value of MaxHealth, which will be defined in subclasses.

Hint(s)
The constructor is protected as we do not want to instanciate a creature without a valid subclass, but still have it accessible to children.

Prototype(s)
protected Creature() { }


Proficiencies/Entities/Item.cs


Items may spawn in the forest, which will be represented by this abstract class. When a Creature steps on an item, the effect will be immediately applied.
Write a new abstract class named Item that inherits from Entity.

Define the method that will be called when the item is stepped on by a creature in the forest. It takes an additional argument Forest as it will contain useful information in the future.
This function must not contain any code, it will be implemented by subclasses.

Warning(s)
You must create the file Proficiencies/Forest.cs now, even if it will be completed later. It is needed for defining the type of the parameter.

Prototype(s)
public abstract void Pickup(Creature creature, Forest forest);


Proficiencies/Smurf.cs


It is now time to implement the friendly entities in the forest: the smurfs.
Write a class Smurf that implements the Creature abstract class.

Information
You may notice we are not writing any constructor for this class, nor the other classes implementing Creature. That is because we already defined a constructor in the abstract class, which will automatically be called when no other constructor is provided.

Implement the MaxHealth getter, which will always return the number 40.

Hint(s)
As a tip, remember you can quickly implement getters with static value the following way. You will need to do this a lot in this section.

Code example(s)
public int TheAnswer => 42;


Proficiencies/Bugs/Bug.cs


We are looking at our next implementation of a creature, this time a hostile one. Write an abstract class that inherits from Creature.
It will be inherited by the various creatures of the forest.

In addition to the inherited attributes, you will also need to add the abstract public getter (without setter) Damage, of type int.

Write a public method that will apply the previously set damage to a given Creature, by reducing its Health value.

Prototype(s)
public void ApplyDamage(Creature creature) { }

Going further
In the scope of this section, we will not be implementing special behaviours for this function, but this method could be made virtual if you wanted to add stronger bugs in the future, with different implementations of the ApplyDamage function.


Proficiencies/Bugs/Spider.cs


Now is the time to implement our first bug!
Write the Spider class that inherits from Bug.

You will need to implement the two missing properties.
  • MaxHealth which is set to 20
  • Damage which equals to 5


Proficiencies/Bugs/BzzFly.cs


Just like Spider, write the BzzFly class that inherits from Bug for representing the black fly from the smurfs.

You will need to implement the two missing properties.
  • MaxHealth which is set to 5
  • Damage which equals to 30


Proficiencies/Exit.cs


Finally, this tile will trigger the end of the game when stepped onto by a smurf. It is the exit leading to the land of sarsaparilla!
This special entity has only one specific behavior: it cannot move, despite what the game may try to do on other entities.
Luckily, given the structure of the code, it is very easy to change this behavior.
Write the Exit class that inherits from Entity.

As this entity cannot move, we must override the default implementation of the method Move from Entity. Write it again such that nothing happens when it gets called.

Prototype(s)
public override void Move(Direction direction) { }


Proficiencies/Forest.cs


Enough types, let us write the actual mechanics behind the forest.
When a smurf leaves the village and enters the forest, random items and bugs are placed on the grid, including the smurf itself. Initial coordinates should never go beyond the range of -10 to 10, both inclusive, but entities may move further during the game.

Additional explanations
You may think you have implemented a lot of grids already this year, but there is a big difference: there will be no matrix or array to place the elements! The entities will be stored in a list, as we only know their position from the X and Y attributes.
The drawback is slower access time when looking for an entity in a specific position, but this allows many more things, such as:
  • There can be multiple entities in the same space
  • You could be more precise in positions and use floating points
  • There is no limit of space, you could place entities infinitely far away without an additional memory cost
3D games are usually storing entities this way, but in 2D games it is more common to have matrix of tiles instead. You will study the former way of storing entities in this practical.

Write a public getter and a private setter Entities for the list of entities in the forest.

Also add public getters and private setters Exit of type Entity for the single exit, and Smurf of type Creature for the single smurf in the forest. They are not set to their final type so that they can bend with the other entities later on.

Hint(s)
You may have noticed the names of the attributes conflict with the names of the classes defined earlier. To work around this issue, you can use the keyword this when you need the attribute (this.Smurf).

Write a public method that returns a list of Entity restricted to the type given as input.

Prototype(s)
public List<Entity> GetEntitiesOfType(EntityType type) { }

Write a public method that returns a list of Entity at the requested coordinates. If there is no entity there, return an empty list.

Prototype(s)
public List<Entity> GetEntitiesAt(int x, int y) { }

Write a private function that will return the direction a source Entity must follow to get closer to a destination Entity.

If two directions seems equivalent, you MUST chose the diagonal first.

Example
If the source entity has coordinates (X=2, Y=3) and the destination has coordinates (X=-1, Y=5), the direction must be NORTH_WEST.

Prototype(s)
private Direction GetDirection(Entity source, Entity destination) { }

Write the constructor of the class. It will initialize the list of entities. The name parameter in the list will match the name of the class. If the name corresponds to none of the entities, throw an ArgumentException.

Warning(s)
Don't forget to assign the Exit and Smurf attributes of the class. If they are not present / not unique, throw an ArgumentException.

Prototype(s)
public Forest(List<(string name, (int X, int Y) position)> entities) { }

Finally, this function will make all the entities of type Creature move towards their designated direction.
The bugs will be moving by themselves and are headed towards the smurf. The smurf is headed towards the exit entity.
Iterate through all items, calculate their direction, and perform the movement.
Bugs must move only one turn out of two, as the smurf is faster. On the first turn, only the smurf moves, and on the second turn, the smurf and the bugs moves. And so on...
If entities collide, some checks must be performed in the following order:
  • If a Smurf collides with an Exit, you must end the loop and return.
  • If a Creature collides with a Item, you must call the Pickup method, then remove the item from the list of entities.
  • If a Smurf collides with a Bug, you must call the ApplyDamage method.
While the smurf has enough health and hasn't reached the exit, you must keep running the loop.
If the exit is reached, return true. Otherwise, he must be rescued and you should return false.

Prototype(s)
public bool MainLoop() { }

Hint(s)
To test your code and see if it works, you can display information on the console, for instance when an item is picked up, but don't forget to remove them before submitting!

Additional explanations
At this point you should start to understand the reason why objects are following this hierarchy. There could be tons of different entities in the game, with special behaviours, but in the end they always have things in common.
The common denominator all entities have is the position, which allows you to process all of them, regardless of what they actually are, if you only need the position.
The same logic goes for bugs. They can attack a Creature which could be a smurf, but also another bug, or any other future creature we might want to add. Once again, the only thing we care about is if the entity respects a certain property (having health). This is the goal of subtyping.
Keep this in mind for the final steps, implementing items!

This item will simply give a health boost to whoever stepped on it.
Write the Berry class inheriting from Item.
As usual, copy over the X and Y attributes.

This item must give an additional 10 points of health to the creature that stepped on it.
